ce:section.ce:para:
The spectral properties of WO3 QDs prepared via ethanol-thermal treatment with different amount of H2O2 were further studied by ultraviolet-visible (UV-vis) absorption and photoluminescence (PL) spectra measurements. Fig. 4
                        a–d shows the UV–vis absorption of WO3 QDs with different amount of H2O2, all the WO3 QDs exhibit the featureless UV–vis absorption extending into the visible region with a absorption peak at around 270nm, and the bang gap (Eg
                        ) is evaluated to be 4.19eV (Fig. S3), corresponding to the previous reports [24,26]. It is obviously found that all the WO3 QDs aqueous solution is pale yellow under daylight, while the WO3 QDs aqueous solution prepared with 0.1 and 0.4mL H2O2 emit light blue luminescence and the WO3 QDs aqueous solution prepared with 0.8 and 1.6mL H2O2 show bright blue luminescence under UV irradiation at 365nm (insets of Fig. 4a–d). The typical PL spectrums of WO3 QDs with different amount of H2O2 are shown in Fig. 4i–l, all the WO3 QDs exhibit excitation-dependent PL behavior, that means the emission wavelength is red shift according to the increase of excitation wavelength. This phenomenon may be attributed to the distribution of emissive taps on the surface of WO3 QDs and the quantum effect [43]. For WO3 QDs (ethanol-treatment with 0.1mL H2O2), the strongest emission is found at 311nm as excited at 280nm, which is ascribed to the band-to-band radiative recombination of photoexicited electrons and holes [22]. The maximum emission peak of WO3 QDs (ethanol-treatment with 0.4mL H2O2) is red–shifted 56nm when excited at 320nm. Whereas, the strongest emission peak of WO3 QDs (ethanol-treatment with 0.8mL H2O2) is 477nm when excited at 380nm, and the maximum emission of WO3 QDs (ethanol-treatment with 1.6mL H2O2) is 485nm as excited at 420nm. The red-shift of the strongest emission peak of WO3 QDs with the increase of H2O2 may result from different size distribution and the oxygen contents of WO3 QDs [17]. Accordingly, the photoluminescence excitation (PLE) spectrums of all the WO3 QDs are shown in Fig. 4e–h. Encouragingly, the as-obtained WO3 QDs exhibit highly fluorescent stability, exposed in air at a room temperature for one hour or even one month, the PL intensity of WO3 QDs shows no significant change (Fig. S4a-4b). Furthermore, Fig. S4c displays that the acidic condition is favorable to the optical properties of WO3 QDs, and they exhibit good stability at different ionic strengths (Fig. S4d).
